The good news: **`OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` still exist** on the MAUI `Application` class and work the same way:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override void OnStart() { /* app launched */ }
    protected override void OnSleep() { /* app backgrounded */ }
    protected override void OnResume() { /* app foregrounded */ }
}
```

However, MAUI also adds a **more granular window-based lifecycle** via `CreateWindow`:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = new Window(new AppShell());

    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* window created */ };
    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* resumed */ };
    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* stopped/backgrounded */ };
    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* closing */ };

    return window;
}
```

For **platform-specific hooks**, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnStop(activity => { /* ... */ }));
#elif IOS
    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.WillTerminate(app => { /* ... */ }));
#endif
});
```

**TL;DR** — Your existing overrides still compile and work. Migrate to the window/platform events only if you need finer control.
